  <section id="about">
  <h2 style="color:#367588">About</h2>
  		<p> Hi! I am a third year grad student in the Department of Mathematics at the University of Chicago, advised by <a href="https://home.ttic.edu/~madhurt/" >Madhur Tulsiani</a> and <a href="https://people.cs.uchicago.edu/~razborov/">Alexander Razborov</a>. Previously, I was an undergrad at Universidad Nacional Autónoma de México where I had the opportunity to work on my thesis under the guidance of <a href="https://www.matem.unam.mx/~rita/mainEng.html">Rita Jiménez Rolland</a>.</p>
  		<p>I am interested in theoretical computer science, especially in combinatorial and topological/geometric ideas. I am broadly interested in high dimensional expanders (HDX), complexity theory, error correction, pseudorrandomness and sampling algorithms. Recently I have been studying constructions of HDX.</p>
  		<p>During my time in undergrad I had the chance to have a taste of areas like algebraic combinatorics, algebraic topology (particularly representation stability) and discrete geometry, all of which I am always keen to learn more about. </p>
  		<p>Here is my <a href="CV.pdf" >CV</a>.</p>
  </section>
